{"cursor":"9818","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Norms' are concepts (sentences) of practical import, oriented to effecting an\naction, rather than conceptual abstractions that describe, explain, and express.\nNormative sentences imply \"ought-to\" types of statements and assertions, in\ndistinction to sentences that provide \"is\" types of statements and assertions.\nCommon normative sentences include commands, permissions, and prohibitions;\ncommon normative abstract concepts include sincerity, justification, and\nhonesty. A popular account of norms describes them as reasons to take action, to\nbelieve, and to feel.\n","linknr":261,"url":"Norm_(philosophy)","recorded":1362892752,"links":20,"instances":["linguistics","principle","government","philosophy","norm","sociology","logic","philosophy","sociology","ethics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Concepts in ethics","Consensus reality","Philosophy of language","Philosophy of law","Social concepts"],"headings":["Types of norms","Major characteristics","See also","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Socrates.png/18px-Socrates.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["sentence","linguistics"],["action","philosophy"],["convention","norm"],["administration","government"],["convention","norm"],["power","sociology"],["cognitivism","ethics"],["convention","norm"],["predicate","logic"],["reduction","philosophy"],["law","principle"],["norm","sociology"]],"members":["sentence","law","administration","reduction","convention","norm","predicate","action","power","cognitivism"],"related":["Sentence_(linguistics)","Imperative_mood","Permission","Reason","Action_(philosophy)","Bel